them” (1986, p 128). Hodder goes further to note, “…archaeological objects are, 
almost by defnition, situated in place and time and in relation to other archaeologi-
cal objects. This network of relationships can be ‘read’” (1986, p 153). Similarly in 
archives, context has been conceptualized as a sort of “text” in which records are 
situated: “Records and archives provide evidence of decisions and activities. They 
derive their meaning and value from a myriad of contextual relationships surround-
ing  their  creation  and  use—relationships  that  have  to  be  documented  and  under-
stood” (Cunningham 2008, p 532). Both examples illuminate that the relationships 
in which an object or a record is enmeshed are part and parcel to their meaning.
The concept of provenance is critical to both archives and archaeology. Context, 
which is related to but also distinct from provenance, is difcult to disentangle from 
the latter. Though frequently confated and used interchangeably, subtle diferences 
distinguish  the  two  concepts.  In  archaeological  excavations,  for  example,  context 
comprises a host of factors (i.e., physical components and spatial relationships) which 
must  be  documented,  including  the  matrix,  the  exact  place  where  the  object  was 
uncovered, and associations to other objects and features (Renfrew and Bahn 2004, 
pp 48–60). Provenance (also sometimes referred to as provenience) typically denotes 
the “fndspot” of an object (Joyce 2012, p 48). In archives, context is considered a 
core  aspect  of  records  and  largely  viewed  as  the  circumstances  surrounding  their 
creation, use, and interpretation (SAA 2023a), whereas provenance is defned as the 
origins or chain of custody (SAA 2023b). Taken as a point of origin, provenance can 
be understood as one moment in the trajectory of an object or record as part of its his-
tory, creation, and use—and thus as one aspect of its context. Increasing recognition 
of the diverse intellectual, social, and cultural circumstances in which objects and 
records come into being and exist complicates a clear demarcation between the two 
concepts in each of these felds. Objects and records often have complex histories, 
and the relationships that defne their contexts are subject to evolution and change. 
At the same time, the unique intellectual traditions of archives and archaeology each 
make such a disentangling of context and provenance a difcult task. For example, 
provenance is frequently reimagined by the archival community, extending and blur-
ring its boundaries to reconfgure it as more fuid and expansive. Archival scholars 
are enhancing and shifting our understandings of provenance to support historically 
marginalized  communities  and  to  contest  and  rethink  the  concept  (e.g.,  Brilmyer 
2022; McCracken and Hogan-Stacey 2023; Wurl 2005). These engagements desta-
bilize and expand provenance. Such a rethinking imbricates provenance and context, 
(further) entangling the two concepts but ultimately creating richer understandings of 
and engagements with objects and records.
Provenance and context make it possible to trace and understand the histories and 
trajectories of objects and records and the network of relationships in which they are 
embedded, aiding in their interpretation. While the concepts hold relevance in other 
felds, such as art history, journalism, and computer science, this article focuses spe-
cifcally on archives and archaeology because they share a vested interest in how 
provenance and context are defned, redefned, and negotiated. Provenance and con-
text are also arguably more relevant than ever to archives and archaeology. As we 
