This article unpacks the distinct ways that archives and archaeology employ prov-
enance and where they might share common ground as a means to enrich discussion, 
introspection, and cross-disciplinary exchange. Context is integral to this discussion 
given the interrelated nature of the two concepts and the uniqueness with which they 
are imbricated and invoked. Archives and archaeology are distinct in their histories, 
theories,  methodologies,  and  aims,  and  yet  they  are  in  many  ways  kindred;  they 
are both oriented toward the material past through the objects they uncover and the 
records they identify and transfer, and more broadly have a vested interest in histori-
cal and cultural preservation. As mainstays for archives and archaeology—both of 
which  foreground  the  origins  and  history  of  records  and  material  culture  in  their 
analyses and documentation—these felds apply a wide variety of nuances and val-
ues to the two concepts, often rethinking their use.
Art history arguably bears relevance to this discussion—especially given its over-
lap with archaeology when objects become the domain of art historical analyses—
and much ink has been devoted to provenance as a lens for art historical scholar-
ship (e.g., Mark 2019). Art history peels back the layers that surround a work of 
art, shedding light on the social, cultural, political, and artistic contexts in which 
it was created, the artist, the style, and other circumstances (Feigenbaum and Reist 
2012). In many cases, provenance in art history is largely concerned with the chain 
of custody and ownership and in ascertaining a work of art’s authenticity, especially 
in the history of collecting (Milosch and Pearce 2019). These are also concerns for 
archives  and  archaeology,  though  the  latter  two  share  an  especially  keen  interest 
in the origins of an object or a set of records (fonds) and fnding, identifying, and 
understanding relationships between objects and records in their original contexts 
of creation and use. Objects and records are at the same time distinctive and kindred 
because  they  are  evidence  of  human  activities.  Moreover,  archival  materials  and 
archaeological fnds are embedded in a network of relationships with other objects, 
records, ecological features, etc., that comprise their context and shed light on their 
nature  (creation,  purpose,  use,  etc.).  Relationships  and  material  plurality  are  fun-
damental to both archives and archaeology, not only as a refection of the realities 
of objects and records, but also in how they are interpreted, and their meaning(s) 
constructed.
This  article  seeks  to  explore  commonalities  and  diferences  in  the  ways  that 
archives and archaeology employ provenance and context and the messiness with 
which they do. This exercise aims to shed light on what each feld might gain from 
the other and how they might rethink their uses of these concepts. My inquiry into 
the ways the two disciplines engage with objects and records through the concepts 
