from which the other can beneft. This article thus ultimately suggests that archives 
and archaeology be in greater conversation with each other as a means to reconsider 
how these concepts are applied to create a richer set of meanings for objects and 
records.
Disentangling provenance and context
Context is both a nebulous and frequently used concept. On the one hand, it is dif-
fcult to describe concretely, but on the other, its meaning is rarely lost on its recipi-
ents.  Context  is  described  as  the  surrounding  circumstances,  the  “environment,” 
or  “setting”  in  which  something  occurs  or  exists  (Merriam-Webster  n.d.).  Deriv-
ing from the Latin contexere (meaning “to weave”) and contextus (meaning “con-
nection”), context was initially used in a literary sense to denote text surrounding 
a particular passage, and eventually the circumstances surrounding a text and his-
torical events more broadly (Burke 2002). The concept was used in Marxism and 
German hermeneutics, expressed through the word Zusammenhang
1
 as “the way in 
which diferent beliefs, customs, and so on “hang together” (Burke 2002, p 158). 
In this vein, context invokes conceptions of culture as a text to be read and inter-
preted,  which  aligns  with  Cliford  Geertz’s  “literary”  view  of  culture  as  context 
(1973,  pp  10,  14).  Context,  in  a  very  real  sense,  can  be  anything  and  everything 
which  becomes  germane  when  one  seeks  to  understand  something  in  the  world. 
Herbert H. Clark and Thomas B. Carlson observed that “the further its uses have 
been extended, the murkier its denotation has become…[it] is a term that is use-
ful precisely because it is vague and general and can accommodate many diferent 
ideas” (1981, p 314). This vagueness makes context difcult to defne and yet a use-
ful trope. Its etymology as “connection,” however, does illuminate what might oth-
erwise be opaque meanings. Context assumes that one cannot understand an object, 
an individual, or a phenomenon without drawing on related objects, individuals, and 
