Context’s chameleon-like nature makes it useful to invoke in a variety of ways, 
but this means its clarity is reliant on the degree to which its meaning can be rea-
sonably inferred. The opposite, however, seems to be true for provenance. On the 
surface, provenance appears much more straightforward and well understood. Origi-
nating  from  the  French  for  “origin”  and  “production,”  and  from  the  Latin  prove-
nire for “come forth, originate, appear, arise” (Online Etymology Dictionary n.d.c), 
provenance refers to something coming into being. Provenience, a related term that 
is largely used in archaeology, derives from the Latinization of provenance and has 
essentially the same meaning (Online Etymology Dictionary n.d.d). Engagements 
with provenance in both archival and archaeological discourse enhance this defni-
tion to underscore the story about where and when something comes into being and 
the journey it undergoes—all of which provides a richer picture of an item and the 
ways it has been shaped by its history. Provenance does not (and should not) repre-
sent merely one moment (i.e., creation) in the history of an object or a record (Millar 
2002, p 8). Rather, the full history and journey that an object or record undertakes 
from one place to the next creates a productive space in which to understand an item 
and the meanings it has accrued over time. This is important to underscore because, 
to a certain degree, provenance is time-dependent, and the most immediately per-
ceived (or, the most recent) “source” of an item may difer depending on where it is 
in its trajectory. For example, in a provenance study of commemorative scarabs from 
the reign of Egyptian Pharaoh Amenhotep III, the provenance is described as the 
last modern collection where they were held (Philips de-Jongh Collection, ca. 1969) 
before being sold on the art market three decades later to presumably private collec-
tions (Clayton 1996). Provenance is sometimes rendered as the last or most recent 
source/location for materials because information about their histories and chains of 
custody are often so fragmentary.
Provenance  is  also  fundamentally  situational  and  placed-oriented—a  fact  that 
spans diferent ways in which the word is invoked, and how the provenance of a 
“thing” is rendered. An illustrative example is the distinctive female fgurine known 
as the “Seated Woman” or “Mistress of Animals,” uncovered in 1961 during excava-
tions of a shrine at the Neolithic/Chalcolithic site Çatalhöyük in Turkey (Mellaart 
1963, pp 83, 93, 97). This fgurine has a provenance (or, a “provenience”) of a spe-
cifc horizontal, vertical, and stratigraphic location in the ground where it was found 
in the shrine in excavation level 2. Expanding out further, the fgurine also has the 
provenance of the site itself (Çatalhöyük, Turkey) where it was found. At the same 
time, the provenance can be the source of the raw materials from which the fgurine 
is  made  (or,  more  precisely,  the  provenance  of  the  clay  the  fgurine  is  made  of), 
and the geographical source from which that material derives (often determined by 
examining its chemical properties). These can all be provenance information for the 
fgurine, none which are exclusive. It is worth noting that the fgurine had a prov-
enance before archaeologists found it and before a chemist or archaeologist analyzed 
its material and chemical composition. The people and communities who created, 
engaged with, traded or gifted, and cared for the fgurine understood its origin and 
source in diferent terms. Its origins may have been a specifc creator or a sacred 
