site. The provenance of the same item for one individual or group thus might difer 
from that of another. Time and space are latent assumptions of provenance and the 
meanings it accrues. Problematizing what is meant by “origin” and “source” can 
encourage broader and more fuid conceptualizations that more accurately refect the 
complex histories and realities of objects and records.
Context is thus understood as relationships and interconnections between things 
in the world which are crucial to their interpretation. Provenance, on the other hand, 
seeks to answer questions about from where something came—not solely its origin 
and source, but the journey and history by which it has been shaped. Based on these 
defnitions alone, context and provenance are two distinct concepts. This provokes 
the question about why they are frequently confated and/or used interchangeably. In 
one important respect, provenance is shaped by contextual factors. Provenance is a 
part of context, but, as far these defnitions are concerned, it is not the same as con-
text. Case in point, the creator (the provenance) of an object or record is one point in 
the web of relationships that surrounds the item (the context). Other contextual ele-
ments—which are not the same as provenance—also afect the object or record. For 
instance, one aspect of the fgurine’s context would be the archaeological tradition 
that the excavator James Mellaart was working within, which infuenced his inter-
pretation that the fgurine represented a mother goddess. As excavations at Çatal-
höyük continued by a new team of archaeologists, and new evidence came to light 
(which have fueled new interpretations infuenced, no doubt, by a diferent archae-
ological tradition (see Tinning 2017)), this fgurine has more recently been inter-
preted as indicative of the power of elders in society rather than of a mother goddess 
cult  (Saini  2023).  This  additional  context—i.e.,  relationships  with  other  evidence 
from the site (especially other fgurines), bundled together with specifc schools of 
archaeological thought—has led to a diferent interpretation of the so-called Mis-
tress of Animals.
As an object or record travels through time and space, everything that happens to 
it or that it encounters along the way forms new connections with which it becomes 
linked. Over its 9000-year history, the Mistress of Animals fgurine accrued difer-
ent meanings, formed diferent connections, and perhaps traveled to diferent places 
before  being  deposited  in  the  shrine  where  it  was  uncovered  by  archaeologists. 
Before being excavated by Mellaart, the fgurine’s journey through Çatalhöyük and 
the community that created it remains unknown. What is known is that following 
excavation it was taken from its shrine at Çatalhöyük and placed in the Museum 
of  Anatolian  Civilizations  in  Ankara  where  it  is  currently  on  display.  This  infor-
mation, albeit incomplete, comprises the fgurine’s known provenance. The artistic 
design of the fgurine, the purpose for which it was made, its relationship to other 
fgurines and objects in situ (and throughout the site as a whole and greater West 
Asia),  and  the  archaeological  traditions  that  have  informed  its  interpretation  over 
time are all examples of aspects of its context. Provenance would answer such ques-
tions as: where is the fgurine from, who created it, where has it traveled? Context 
would answer such questions as: for what purpose was the fgurine made, why was 
it designed the way it was, what were the historical, social, cultural, economic, and 
physical/environmental  circumstances  in  which  its  provenance  story  developed? 
Context can be viewed as the cause for the fgurine’s existence, while provenance is 
