an efect. It is the contextual relationships that shape its provenance, and thus what 
can be known about it. Taken together, provenance and context provide a fuller pic-
ture of the fgurine so that we understand where it came from, where it has been, 
why it was fashioned in a specifc way, and the conditions that shaped it.
The archival reconfguration of provenance
Provenance and the centralization of archives
Despite the ways in which provenance and context are distinct, when it comes to 
a discussion of records, they have become entangled and confated in archival and 
mainstream discourse. This entanglement surfaced in the latter half of the twentieth 
century when archivists began to rethink provenance in an attempt to better repre-
sent the complexities of archives in the world in which they exist (Douglas 2017, p 
31). The reconfguration of provenance and its intertwining with context is related to 
questions about what provenance really is—which, I argue, is connected to a sincere 
desire to understand how a particular fonds is meaningful and why it matters.
Before its establishment as an archival principle proper, provenance long existed 
as a method (Horsman 2002, pp 4–10). Recognition of the importance of keeping 
records together based on shared origins, functions, or activities survives in exam-
ples from early societies in West Asia and North Africa. For instance, the personal 
archives of a man named Ilim–ilimma from the town of Alalakh were kept and found 
in  the  king’s  palace,  evidencing  his  importance  and  perhaps  his  connection  with 
the royal family (Podany 2022, pp 343–344). Administrative records from the pal-
aces, such as those found in Ugarit, were typically located in specifc rooms, often 
(but not consistently) in interrelated aggregates that seem tied to specifc functions 
(Whitt 1993
2
). In Mesopotamia, records in the form of clay tablets inscribed with 
cuneiform were often kept in storage rooms in palaces or private residences—and 
in cases where archaeological excavations documented the fndspots of records in 
situ, their contents along with other objects and features in association can be exam-
ined to ascertain provenance information (and provide context). Having information 
about where records were stored and how they were kept together (i.e., arranged) is 
critical to understanding their provenance and arguably refects a concern by ancient 
recordkeepers  to  respect  des  fonds.  But  the  precise  reasons  why  certain  records 
were stored and grouped together can evade modern understandings (Yeo 2021, pp 
177–179). The storage and arrangement of records often serve more as evidence of 
their  uses  and  the  activities  of  which  they  were  a  part,  rather  than  of  their  crea-
tion, origins, and trajectories. As with all historial and archaeological evidence, an 
incomplete picture remains until, and if, more evidence is uncovered.
