The practice of creating, keeping, and using archives has a long history, and soci-
eties developed diferent ways to manage records. For example, there is evidence of 
the registration of documents and “record group” arrangements from ancient Rome, 
and the keeping of outgoing correspondence and the creation of inventories in the 
Middle Ages (Posner 1972, pp 186–223; Posner 2006, pp 23–25). The administra-
tion of archives was largely a decentralized afair, and it was not until the French 
Revolution  that  archives  were  centrally  managed  by  the  state.  Ernst  Posner  notes 
of this critical moment that “[t]he conception of general archives establishments as 
places where records of the whole state administration, central as well as provin-
cial, should be preserved did not and could not materialize until an external impulse 
was  received  and  an  entirely  new  attitude  toward  archives  developed”  (2006,  p 
25).  Provenance  emerged  as  a  formal  archival  concept  in  the  mid-late  nineteenth 
century based on rules developed by French and Prussian state archives to group 
together  records  with  a  shared  origin  (respect  des  fonds  in  1841  and  Provenien-
zprinzip  in  1881,  respectively).  Its  emergence  is  largely  viewed  as  pragmatic  but 
also in response to the importance accreted to understanding the origins of historical 
sources (Douglas 2017, pp 27–30), perhaps due in part to the need for consistency 
amid the large-scale central administration of records. The concept gained currency 
when archives became conceptualized as an “organic whole, a living organism” due 
to the Dutch Manual published in 1898 (Muller, Feith, and Fruin 2003, p 19, cited in 
Douglas 2017, p 29), which advocated for keeping separate such “wholes.”
These conceptions of archives and provenance, particularly in the Dutch Manual, 
assumes a static quality to the “organic wholes” that exist in relatively stable envi-
ronments, and whose arrangement refects the structure of the entity that created the 
“whole.” Archivists in the latter half of the twentieth century began understanding 
provenance in slightly diferent terms, as a more complex phenomenon. In North 
America, provenance was initially debated and considered less crucial than it was to 
Europeans archives where records stretched back centuries (Nesmith 1993). Man-
aging records of considerable age and extent proved to not be the only argument 
for  respecting  provenance;  archivists  in  the  USA  and  Canada  began  to  recognize 
the utility of provenance in light of the challenges raised by information retrieval, 
bureaucratic complexities, and electronic records (Nesmith 1993). This recognition, 
too, gave rise to explorations of “…the full, rich, contextual power of provenance” 
(emphasis  mine;  Nesmith  1993,  p  10).  Terry  Cook,  for  example,  argued  that  the 
fonds is an intellectual and abstract construct, highlighting the multiple relationships 
that surround records (1993). He noted that records which comprise a fonds are not 
necessarily in one place—rather, they can be physically dispersed as a result of the 
creator’s functions, uses, and activities. Cook alighted on the fact that provenance 
needs to be mapped through “relationship linking” (Cook 1992, p 33), and that to 
understand the fonds its context must be illuminated. Peter Scott’s earlier interven-
tion in this space likewise acknowledged the plurality implicit in records creation, 
namely through multiple creators (1966).
Archivists  increasingly  foregrounded  context  as  part  and  parcel  to  under-
standing  and  describing  fonds,  especially  through  “societal  and  intellectual  con-
texts” (Nesmith 2002, p 35). This expansion of provenance to encompass societal 
dimensions  emerged  from  realizations  that  Indigenous  peoples  were  the  creators 
