of  archives  to  which  they  had  previously  not  been  attributed  (Nesmith  2015,  pp 
286–287;  Nesmith  2006).  What  we  mean  when  we  talk  about  the  “origins”  of 
records, and indeed, who is the creator requires transcending our own positionalities 
and the limiting Western frameworks within which we operate. The postmodern turn 
in archival discourse further propelled archivists to embrace the context of records, 
to focus “on the context behind the content; on the power relationships that shape 
the documentary heritage” (Cook 2001, p 25). This also led to new terms for prove-
nance—for example, Tom Nesmith introduced “societal provenance” to describe the 
social and cultural origins of records, describing a variety of contextual relationships 
that shape those records (2006). Where does provenance begin and context end, and 
vice versa, in Nesmith’s conceptual neologism? Is he in fact describing context and 
not provenance? These ideas, no doubt, opened provenance up to the broad(er) pos-
sibilities of context, paving the way for other archival conceptual expansions.
Conceptual neologisms
In  its  description  of  the  impetus  for  the  News  Provenance  Project,  the  New  York 
Times poses the question: “As a news photo travels around the Internet, how might 
we  ensure  the  full  context  of  that  photo  travels  with  it?”  (News  Provenance  Pro-
ject 2020). Yet what the project describes as “context” resonates more closely with 
provenance (e.g., editorial history, travel history across the internet, original news 
source, creator, date of creation, etc.), despite both words being used interchange-
ably on the site. One could argue that such a confation of terms when the whole 
(context) is used to represent the part (provenance) is not as likely to cause confu-
sion. Likewise, in the current archival literature provenance and context are used 
interchangeably and frequently confated (Cline 2022, p 129), but in most of these 
cases the part (provenance) is used to represent the whole (context). The archival 
literature is replete with examples of provenance’s frequent reconfguration, stretch-
ing its boundaries to create greater overlap with context. Like “societal provenance” 
introduced by Nesmith, these reconfgurations have included proposals for hybrid 
context–provenance neologisms. Lori Poldolsky Nordland, for example, introduced 
“secondary provenance” to describe “…additional layers of context” for Ac ko mok 
ki’s map (2004, p 149). Along similar lines, Heather MacNeil described context as 
the  “framework  of  action  in  which  the  record  participates,”  an  element  of  which 
is the notion of provenancial context, “…the creating body, its mandate, structure, 
and functions” (2000, p 95). This defnition of provenancial context is one of four 
types  of  contexts  defned  by  the  InterPARES  project.  The  latter  defnes  context 
as the “framework in which a record is created, used, and maintained” and prov-
enance as “the relationships between records and the organizations or individuals 
that created, accumulated and/or maintained and used them in the conduct of per-
sonal or corporate activity” (InterPARES Trust 2018). These two defnitions from 
InterPARES, however, draw a faint line between context and provenance; context 
is described in terms of its creation, use, and maintenance (though not in terms of 
its origins, per se), whereas provenance is defned in terms of relationships. These 
examples illuminate the ways in which provenance and context are often symbiotic, 
770
  Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781
reconfgured, used interchangeably, and manifest as new terms to describe records 
and their realities.
Another  term  that  surfaces  in  discussions  about  archives  and  the  imbricated 
nature  of  provenance  and  context  is  “archival  bond.”  Luciana  Duranti  describes 
archival  bond  as  an  inherent  relationship  between  records,  conjuring  the  notion 
of context. She cautions, however, that archival bond should not be equated with 
context, given context’s external nature and the fact that archival bond represents 
internal  relationships  within/between  records  critical  to  determining  their  mean-
ing (1997, p 217). Archives derive meaning from their organic plurality, and are, 
following Elio Lodolini, “…tied together by a necessary, primary, and determined 
bond” (1989, p 40, see also Duranti 1997, footnote 8, p 216). For Duranti, archival 
bond is akin to the connective tissue that incrementally forms as records in the same 
aggregation are created as the result of the same activity through the actions of a 
creator(s) (1997, p 216). Like MacNeil, Duranti foregrounds four diferent types of 
contexts as germane to records: juridical/administrative context, provenancial con-
text, procedural context, and documentary context. She notes that the latter, docu-
mentary context, “…results from the totality of the archival bonds arising within 
an  archival  fonds”  (p  217,  footnote  10).  Taken  together,  archival  bond  en  masse 
comprises a specifc kind of context in a documentary sense, perhaps because these 
bonds are external to each other in cases where bonds between materials in diferent 
boxes or folders are concerned.
Despite  Duranti’s  insistence  that  archival  bond  is  not  context,  it  nevertheless 
bears a remarkable similarity to context in its core defnition. The defnition of con-
text does not necessarily assume an inherent externality. Context is fundamentally 
about  relationships  between  things,  which  is  also  central  to  the  idea  of  archival 
bond. Moreover, the etymology of context grounds the word in an original literary 
meaning in which diferent parts of the same text inform each other: “the parts of a 
writing or discourse which precede or follow, and are directly connected with, some 
other  part  referred  to  or  quoted”  (Online  Etymology  Dictionary  n.d.a).  The  leap 
from the relationship between the same parts of a text to the relationship between 
records in the same aggregation is a short distance. Similar to a text in which a par-
ticular passage is analyzed and interpreted in light of the preceding or following pas-
sages, so too can this defnition of context apply to records in aggregate which have 
relationships with those records that precede or follow each other and would other-
wise be conceptualized as sharing a bond. As discussed further below, archival bond 
is in many ways similar to the notion context that is invoked in archaeology.
Finding the human(ity) in provenance
The  development  of  new  terminology  to  more  clearly  articulate  the  realities  of 
records’ creation, use, and engagement re-envision provenance and context. These 
re-envisionings  are  no  doubt  the  result  of  the  contested  place  provenance  has  in 
archival theory and practice, especially because of its relationship with the concept 
of the fonds, which has itself been much debated. Laura Millar, for instance, advo-
cates for an expansion of provenance (and a decentering of the fonds) to include 
771
Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781 
creator history, records history, and custodial history (2002), while Peter Horsman 
seeks  to  (re)defne  provenance  in  terms  of  respect  des  fonds  (2002).  Others  have 
advocated for new approaches to description and to the conception of the fonds. The 
archival literature is also replete with acknowledgments that provenance is unsta-
ble as a concept (e.g., Lemieux 2016, p 8), and that the reality of records requires 
more expansive and generous thinking. Case in point, the International Council on 
Archives’  Records  in  Contexts  (RiC)  conceptual  model  calls  for  an  expansion  of 
the concept of provenance given the complexities of creatorship and of records to 
one another in the digital age, noting that “[b]oth the fonds and the records con-
tained in it exist in layers of interconnected contexts, past, present, and future” (RiC 
IAD 2021). Along the way, new proposals for thinking about concepts of the fonds, 
original order, and arrangement have been introduced and debated, making clear the 
ways in which archival terminology is interconnected; thus, the reconfguration of 
one term has implications for the broader archival terminological ecosystem.
A fundamental reason why the archival community has moved toward reconfgur-
ing provenance is to better represent and articulate accurate acknowledgements of 
the social and intellectual factors that generate and shape records. It is important to 
not forget the humanity integral to and within records, how they come into being and 
change over time, and how we understand the relationships within which they are 
enmeshed. There is also perhaps a practical dimension to the inevitable intertwining 
of the two concepts; it would simply be impossible to adequately describe records 
without drawing on known aspects of both their provenance and context. Part and 
parcel to these re-conceptualizations of provenance is an expressed need to acknowl-
edge the important role of context born out of necessity. The provenance of records 
is contingent on place, time, and people. Records are vital components of communi-
ties—and communities are vital components of records (Bastian 2003b). It matters 
where records originate, especially to the communities who create and engage with 
them (Bastian 2003a). Communities and records can also be dispersed, particularly 
when considering intellectual networks of exchange, which has implications for how 
we think about provenance (Anderson 2021). But provenance can be fragmentary 
and thus our understanding of it incomplete. What is at stake in these cases is the 
loss of humanity in records, or, conversely, one’s ability to gain an understanding 
of the loss of humanity such records might evince. Little to no provenance informa-
tion can create precarity in records, which speaks volumes about how the humanity 
of minoritized individuals has been documented (or not) and perceived (Brilmyer 
2022). Provenance has been arguably understood “to protect the context of records” 
(Pan 2015, p 152). What is clear is that traditional conceptions of provenance, or 
even provenance by itself, do not always adequately capture the people, places, and 
intellectual traditions that shape records and in which they are documented.
While not an exhaustive catalog of provenance (and context) in archival thought, 
these  examples  challenge  archivists  to  think  about  what  provenance  is  and  is  not 
and what it might aspire to be. At the same time, these examples require a care-
ful consideration of the relationship between provenance and context, understand-
ing where they are distinct, and how and when they might productively inform each 
other. The ways in which provenance has been stretched and reconfgured as context 
raises the question about why we are not using context in these cases to describe the 
772
  Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781
rich and complex set of circumstances that give rise to records. Should these exam-
ples encourage us to radically rethink provenance and embrace hybrid provenance-
context neologisms? Or,  should  we  see provenance and  context as  fundamentally 
inseparable? What can be said is that collapsing the space between provenance and 
context  illuminates  the  archival  community’s  desire  for  a  more  expansive  under-
standing of the breadth, complexity, and humanity in and of records.
Provenance, Provenience, and Being in Archaeological Context
Provenance, antiquarianism, and evolutionary change
In  archaeology,  a  diferent  kind  of  terminological  landscape  has  developed.  Like 
archives, provenance is a fundamental concept for archaeology. However, one nota-
ble diference is archaeology’s use of its variant, provenience. While provenience 
and provenance roughly have the same meaning, the ways in which they have been 
used requires unpacking. Another way in which archives and archaeology difer is in 
the latter’s more deliberate foregrounding of context, using it in a way that is clearly 
distinctive  from  provenance/provenience.  Archaeology  has  also  devoted  less  ink 
than archives to examining the conceptual nuances (and possibilities) of its termi-
nology and the use of provenance and context (Lyman 2012). Nonetheless, as with 
archival discourse, provenance and context in archaeology are deeply interrelated 
and have a symbiotic relationship, and they are far from stable concepts.
Archaeology  and  its  relationship  with  museums  and  museum  collections—and 
the sometimes lack of or dubious provenance information—has resulted in questions 
about the feld’s history. Interest in material evidence about the human past has a 
long history, frst thought to be documented in the reign of the Neo-Babylonian king 
Nabonidus in the sixth-century BCE (van Buren 1925; Bahn 2014). The practice of 
collecting antiquities and performing amateur excavations also has a long and global 
history (Bahn 2014). The material past has always had a presence in the daily lives 
of people, and indeed, people today we would consider “ancient” reinscribed new 
meanings on sites and material culture that were “historical” to them (Wade 2023), 
in addition to collecting antiquities from their own cultures (Bahn 2014, p 2). How-
ever, antiquarianism took a colonial turn in Europe’s early modern period, introduc-
ing ideological constructs about power and alterity based on the consumption, in 
part, of the material culture and heritage of the peoples from whom they looted and 
took. Western powers, for instance, have repeatedly appropriated and taken the rich 
material culture of Egypt’s pharaonic past, especially in the name of science (e.g., 
Wilkinson 2020). To understand the deep legacies of colonialism in the excavation, 
removal, and/or dispersal of ancient societies’ material culture, one only has to look 
at the history of one of Egypt’s most famed and contested objects, the Rosetta Stone, 
which remains displayed in the British Museum despite calls for it to be returned to 
Egypt (Romo 2022). Today, archaeology faces a reckoning of its colonial roots, in 
which provenance plays a critical role.
As a Western scientifc discipline, archaeology emerged in the mid-late nine-
teenth century as the professional scholarly study of humans and societies through 
773
Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781 
material  culture  and  ancestor  remains  (Renfrew  and  Bahn  2004).  At  the  same 
time that archaeology became a formalized discipline, ideas about evolutionary 
change and natural selection gained traction following the publication of Charles 
Darwin’s  Origin  of  Species  in  1859.  Such  ideas  no  doubt  infuenced  archaeol-
ogy’s  development,  which  focused  on  placing  human  societies  and  their  mate-
rial  culture  within  chronologies  and  classifcations  that  refected  notions  about 
evolution  (Renfrew  and  Bahn  2004)—an  idea  that  has  evolved,  been  debated, 
and become entrenched in how archaeology has been practiced. Indeed, archae-
ologists would use evolution as a model for cultural development into the twen-
tieth century. Leslie White, as a prominent example, advocated universal cultural 
evolution as a framework for understanding human societies (Barnard 2000, pp 
39–40). V. Gordon Childe made similar arguments based on cultural evolution, 
but through a theory of historical change that was very much infuenced by Marx-
ist ideas about development and production in what came to be known as “cul-
ture-historical archaeology” (Jones 2002, p 12). Childe saw large-scale historical 
and  cultural  change  progressing  through  marked  socioeconomic  shifts,  through 
what he coined the “Neolithic Revolution” and the “Urban Revolution” in West 
Asia.
Other archaeologists and anthropologists moved away from grand models of cul-
tural change. Instead, they focused on specifc local cultural developments through 
the lens of historical-particularistic and ecological models, such as those proposed 
by  Franz  Boas  and  Julian  Steward  (Barnard  2000,  pp  100–101).  Archaeology, 
however, returned to its “scientifc” roots in the form of processualism in the mid-
twentieth century (Wilson 1975, pp 1–26). Processual archaeology styled itself as a 
scientifc approach to identify processes of cultural change and adaptation within a 
set of economic, social, and environmental systems. Indeed, by drawing from sys-
tems thinking, “[m]embers of the process school view human behavior as a point 
of  overlap  (or  “articulation”)  between  a  vast  number  of  systems,  each  of  which 
encompasses both cultural and noncultural phenomena” (Flannery 1967, p 120). It 
asserted itself as an approach closely intertwined with the concerns of anthropology 
(as it was conceptualized at that time) by drawing from the scientifc method as a 
model for forming and testing hypotheses to answer specifc questions about cultural 
change, seeing culture as its laboratory (Binford 1962).
The criticism that processualism was positivistic and behavioristic—and too nar-
rowly focused given that it did not take into account religious, symbolic, and social 
phenomena—led  other  archaeologists  to  develop  alternative  ideas  in  the  1970s. 
Post-processual archaeology, by contrast, eschewed grand narratives about change 
and  “scientifc  objectivity.”  Infuenced  by  French  Marxist  anthropology,  structur-
alism,  and  postmodernism  more  generally,  post-processual  archaeology  situates 
itself as subjective and interpretative, and sees germane the ways in which gender, 
identity, and power afect the archaeological record (Trigger 2006, pp 444–478). A 
strand that emerged from this movement was contextual archaeology—an approach 
developed  by  Ian  Hodder  that  holistically  considers  the  broad  cultural  context  of 
archaeological data and the ways in which data are interconnected (Trigger 2006, 
pp  455–456).  Contextual  archaeology  centers  context  as  an  abstract  concept  in 
archaeological analysis, rendering the archaeological record as a text to be read and 
774
  Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781
interpreted (Hodder 1986, pp 121-155). This approach ultimately situates archaeol-
ogy as hermeneutics and the archaeologist as an interpreter of objects.
Amid developments in archaeology in the late nineteenth century, provenience 
began to be consistently employed as a concept (Kolb 2014, p 6173), roughly around 
the same the time as the uptake of provenance as a principle by the archival pro-
fession. Archaeologists came to increasingly view provenience as vital documenta-
tion due to a variety of factors, especially interest by museums in purchasing objects 
from excavations (which would have little research value sans provenience) and the 
fact that the questions being asked of the archaeological record had begun to evolve 
(Lyman 2012). These in turn infuenced feld methods and the extent to which (and 
how)  an  object  was  documented  in  situ—i.e.,  in  “its  original  place  or  position” 
(Online Etymology Dictionary n.d.b). As feld methods became more formalized, 
so too did the principles underlying these methods, in tandem with the importance 
accorded to the systematic collection of data for the study of successive change over 
time. But with the post-processual turn in archaeology, context came to hold greater 
relevance in archaeology, becoming arguably the centerpiece and guiding light of 
the archaeological enterprise.
Provenance and/or provenience?
As aforementioned, provenance and provenience have the same meaning as “origin” 
or “source,” but the latter is a Latinization of the word (Online Etymology Diction-
ary n.d.d). Despite this shared defnition, archaeologists sometimes use these two 
diferent  words  to  describe  the  same  thing—and  sometimes  to  describe  diferent 
things altogether (even with the same word). It is not uncommon to see both prov-
enance and provenience used interchangeably in archaeological discourse. Theoreti-
cally, these words are variations of each other, though a deeper examination reveals 
the ways in which tensions and conventions based on dialect, geography, and sub-
feld permeate their use.
Provenance has a tendency to be used for archaeological objects that have been 
placed into art historical contexts (Joyce 2012, p 48). Provenience, on the other hand, 
is a concept situated by place—i.e., the exact vertical, horizontal, and stratigraphic 
location (or fndspot) of an object uncovered during excavation (Renfrew and Bahn 
2004, pp 54, 111). It is an empirical data point, a precise physical location in a four-
dimensional space. Prior to the nineteenth century, excavations had begun to record 
location information but focused on the strata in which the objects had been found 
rather than the precise spot; it was not until the late nineteenth century that prove-
nience was considered to be important data to record (Lyman 2012, pp 213–215). 
A study of archaeology textbooks spanning from 1904 to 2010 (mostly from North 
America) indicates that provenience has been consistently used to denote “position” 
or “location,” but it did not start being consistently defned until the 1970s (Lyman 
2012, pp 220–221).
Rosemary A. Joyce notes that in an art historical and museological vein, prov-
enance is conceptualized as an object’s entire itinerary while provenience (the fnds-
pot) is a fxed moment in an object’s history and therefore one point in its trajectory 
775
Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781 
(2012, pp 48–49). They thus intersect at a specifc moment in an object’s history. 
In the North American use of the terms, “[p]rovenance thus signifes the place of 
origin for a material whereas provenience signifes where an object (regardless of 
material type) is found” (Lyman 2012, p 211). However, even with this distinction 
in mind, usage of the words varies in additional ways. Provenience is largely pre-
ferred by archaeologists in North America, whereas provenance is favored by Euro-
pean archaeologists to describe a fndspot (Joyce 2012, p 49). But the diferences do 
not stop here. While provenience/provenance is commonly agreed as being about 
an object’s origins, the convention in classical archaeological and art historical tra-
ditions  is  to  see  provenance  as  akin  to  the  history  of  an  object—its  résumé  even 
(Price and Burton 2011, p 213). Both terms are used to either describe the origin 
of  an  object  or  the  precise  location  where  the  object  was  found  (as  an  empirical 
data point). Once the object has been uncovered and removed from the place where 
it was found, though, provenance appears to be more consistently used to describe 
the itinerary and history an object has undergone, particularly in art historical and 
museum settings.
Provenience can also have slightly diferent meanings based on whether it means 
where an object was uncovered (by archaeologists) or where it originated (its geo-
chemical/material composition or source). Specifcally, archaeological chemistry is 
concerned with the place of origin by analyzing the composition of an object and 
tracing the geological source (Price and Burton 2011, pp 213–218). Such analyses 
can attempt to determine where an object was made and by whom. But geochemi-
cal  provenience  studies  can  answer  other  questions  by  analyzing  the  composition 
of objects, such as the morphological typology of objects and the nature of ancient 
technologies (e.g., Braekmans et al. 2019). And yet, sometimes provenance is used 
to  describe  the  geochemical  framework  of  archaeological  analysis.  Charles  Kolb 
describes provenance studies as “…a diagnosis of the origin of the materials that 
comprise the object, the location or site where it was produced or fabricated, who 
made it, and why and for what purposes. A related set of questions, often with com-
plex answers, is how the object was relocated from its place of origin to location at 
which it was recovered” (2014, p 6172). Usage varies further by subfeld. For exam-
ple, historical archaeologists use provenance in a geochemical sense, and proveni-
ence as the fndspot of the object during excavation (Hauser 2008, p 162, cited in 
Kolb 2014). As these examples indicate, to understand what “provenance” and “pro-
venience” might mean in any particular case minimally requires information about 
dialect or geographical origin of the archaeologist and the tradition or subfeld of 
archaeology in which it is being used.
The power of context
These diferences between provenance and provenience seem mostly driven by dia-
lect,  geography,  and  subfeld.  Where  archaeology  does  appear  to  have  more  con-
sensus is in its utilization of context, but even this term has evolved and come to 
represent broader and more abstract relationships. Context in archaeology is the gen-
erally articulated as the “four-dimensional, spatial–temporal matrix that comprises 
776
  Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781
both a cultural and noncultural environment, and that can apply to a single artifact 
or to a constellation of sites” but it has also been interpreted as the broader ecosys-
tem or environment in which a site is enmeshed (Butzer 1980). Like provenience, it 
manifests as a physical and specifc place in most defnitions, but it is much broader 
and answers questions about not only where an object was uncovered, but what kind 
of sediment it was located in, its association with other objects, etc. (Hirst 2018). 
Context bundles together empirical provenience data and information such as infer-
ences  made  about  objects  found  in  association  with  each  other  (Lyman  2012,  pp 
212–213). In this sense, context is a unifying concept in archaeology, a means to 
aggregate data and inferences to form the basis for interpretation. Like the concept 
of archival bond, context places precedence on relationships between objects, espe-
cially taken together as a whole. While the notion of the archaeological matrix-as-
context appears to be a reasonably agreed upon and undisputed meaning, the term 
has evolved in archaeological thought to encompass social, economic, and environ-
mental factors (e.g., Johnsen and Olsen 1992). But even then, these interpretations 
of  context  align  with  its  core  etymological  meaning,  taking  disparate  and  related 
aspects of an object’s reality, relationships in which it is embedded, and “weaving 
them together” to produce a fuller understanding and aid to interpretation.
Context  as  a  concept  has  gained  specifc  prominence  with  the  development  of 
contextual archaeology, which frmly established context as an abstract concept and 
not just the physical matrix in which objects were deposited as being relevant to 
archaeological  analysis.  Context,  which  is  always  shifting,  and  diferent  contexts 
will prevail in diferent settings, will thus always be subject to the interpretation of 
the archaeologist. But the interpretation of context requires a thorough process of 
investigation: “[t]he task of the archaeologist is to go round and round the data in a 
hermeneutic spiral, looking for relationships, ftting pieces of the jigsaw together” 
(Shanks and Hodder 1995, p 15). Interpretation is a process and requires consider-
ing multiple data points together with multiple relationships between them and other 
objects and phenomena. Though not without its critics (e.g., Jones 2007, pp 78–84), 
contextual  archaeology  illustrates  the  pitfalls  of  interpreting  archaeological  data 
divorced from its cultural context (Trigger 2006, p 455). Its advocacy of archaeo-
logical evidence as local, situated, contingent, and yet defned by interconnections 
with a universe of data and phenomena seeks to open the archaeological record up 
to a broad understanding of the human experience—both from the positionalities of 
archaeologists and the past people whose lives they would interpret and understand.
When archaeologists excavate a site and uncover objects, they fnd them in situ, 
where they were deposited as part of their itinerary. Place is important in archae-
ology,  both  in  terms  of  where  an  object  derived  (geographically,  etc.)  and  where 
it  was  deposited  before  its  encounter  with  archaeologists.  Despite  the  messiness 
with which provenance and provenience are employed, they still largely remain dis-
tinct from context. Context, however, has both a materiality (in the case where it is 
conceptualized as the matrix surrounding an object) and an intangibility where the 
factors relevant to its existence and interpretation must be inferred from a variety 
of relationships to the object in question. But context can be difcult to ascertain 
(Thompson 2024), and provenance/provenience information can also be lost or left 
undocumented. Much is at stake when this information is missing, but much is to be 
777
Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781 
gained when it is carefully recorded. The tensions between provenance and proveni-
ence reveal a desire to know and understand an object fully and the idiosyncrasies of 
language and archaeology. This foregrounding of context, however, ultimately draws 
archaeology and archives more closely together, underscoring how they are funda-
mentally kindred. Archivists’ quests to reimagine provenance and intertwine it with 
context is indicative of the same desire that archaeologists have to understand the 
range of phenomena and relationships that shape the archaeological record through 
approaches  like  post-processual  and  contextual  archaeology.  Each  of  these  felds 
recognizes the complex world in which objects and records are created, used, and 
interpreted, and that no object or record is an island.
Toward a kindred context and provenance
Elisabeth  Kaplan  argued  that  anthropology  and  archives  are  akin  in  many  ways, 
particularly  as  agents  of  representation  and  power  (2002).  Archaeology  shares 
these same traits with archives, and especially with respect to its orientation toward 
the past. But, as this article demonstrates, they are fundamentally kindred in that 
they both maintain a symbiotic relationship between provenance and context, and 
the terminological messiness that can result from this relationship. They have each 
approached this messiness in diferent ways, though, which arguably holds valuable 
lessons  for  the  other.  Archives  has  illustrated  a  keen  desire  to  reimagine  its  con-
ceptual landscape, recognizing the necessity of stretching the boundaries of prov-
enance to capture a richer and fuller story for records. This has led to an inevitable 
blurriness with the concept of context. Archaeology has sought to demarcate frm 
boundaries between provenance and context, recognizing the utility and importance 
for these distinctions. Archaeologists have also embraced context, realizing the ways 
in which it is crucial to archaeological interpretation—both in the tangible, physi-
cal sense, and in terms of the abstract forces and relationships that have shaped the 
archaeological record. Yet, inconsistencies in the uses of provenance and proveni-
ence have emerged in an attempt to describe (sometimes) slightly diferent aspects 
of objects. What archaeologists might gain from archival ruminations with prove-
nance is the perhaps the need to experiment with and develop new terminology as 
a means to assuage the confusion to which this tension leads, and the encourage-
ment to step outside of confnes of these terms and expand their possibilities—while 
maintaining, of course, their lucid terminological landscape. Archivists, on the other 
hand,  might  take  heed  of  the  clear  distinctions  between  context  and  provenance/
provenience in archaeology, and ultimately come to consensus about what we mean 
when we talk about provenance for archives without losing the richness of their re-
imaginings of this concept.
Michael Shanks and Ian Hodder note that “A pot without provenance is of lim-
ited value to archaeological interpretation. It has long been recognized that placing 
things in context is fundamental to understanding the past” (1995, p 14). Neither 
archivists nor archaeologists would disagree with this statement. But what is impor-
tant about what Shanks and Hodder illustrate in this case is the relationship between 
provenance  and  context—a  relationship  that  itself  is  a  kind  of  context  which  is 
778
  Archival Science (2024) 24:761–781
important  to  maintain.  Provenance  and  context  each  have  more  power—reinforce 
each other, even—when taken together.
Case in point, another notable way that archives and archaeology bear similar-
ity relates to the process of removing/transferring records, objects, and environmen-
tal samples from the original site(s) of creation and use. Although less destructive 
methods  can  be  employed  in  lieu  of  excavation  (e.g.,  remote  sensing  methods), 
archaeology  is  widely  described  as  a  destructive  science  because  a  site  must  be 
destroyed in order to be understood. Likewise, archivists or creators/donors must be 
very careful when removing records and transferring them to an archives to ensure 
the original order of the materials is not lost (which is not to say that records are not 
transferred to archival repositories in a variety of ways, and thus this is an idealistic 
scenario). Following this removal (i.e., “excavation” in archaeology and “transfer/
donation” in archives), neither archaeologist nor archivist can objectively “re-con-
textualize” the objects or records (e.g., Jones 2002, pp 63–82). In both cases, the 
context is destroyed, or lost, making it crucial to document the circumstances sur-
rounding objects and records. Critical to this process is maintaining the relationship 
between objects and/or records and documenting their “original” location and other 
factors  and  circumstances  about  their  creation,  use,  and  maintenance.  In  an  ideal 
world, all this information should be gathered, documented, and made available so 
that we can know (and trust) what we see and develop our own interpretations. In 
no small way, archives and archaeology share this same goal. But each stand to gain 
greater understandings if they can encourage each other to be both a bit more precise 
and a bit more expansive.
